{
  "title": "Combining importlib and Typing for Production Code in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer demonstrates how to leverage the powerful features of importlib and typing modules in Python 3.12+ to enhance modularity, code organization, and type hinting for production-ready code.",
  "key_points": [
    "Utilize importlib's `import_module` function for dynamic module imports",
    "Employ typing annotations to improve readability and support IDE autocompletion",
    "Leverage Generics from the typing module to create reusable type-safe classes or functions",
    "Use import_aliases for clearer imports with long module names"
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from typing import Generic, TypeVar, cast\nT = TypeVar('T')\nclass MyGeneric(Generic[T]):\n    def my_method(self, arg: T) -> None:\n        ...\n\nmy_module = import_module('mymodule')  # Dynamic module import"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from typing import List, Optional\ndef greet(name: Optional[str], message: str = 'Hello, World!') -> List[str]:\n    return [message + (', ' + name if name else '')]  # Type hinting with default arguments"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Note: The examples provided are based on Python 3.12, but many of these techniques will also work in earlier versions with appropriate adjustments.",
    "Always check the Python documentation and third-party libraries' official repositories for the latest updates."
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "Be aware that dynamic imports may impact the startup performance of your application due to the time required to load modules at runtime.",
    "While type hinting can improve code readability and IDE support, it does not perform any runtime checks for incorrect usage of types. Ensure you have appropriate unit tests in place."
  ]
}

code_examples.code:
from typing import Generic, TypeVar, cast
T = TypeVar('T')
class MyGeneric(Generic[T]):
    def my_method(self, arg: T) -> None:
        ...

my_module = import_module('mymodule')  # Dynamic module import

from typing import List, Optional
def greet(name: Optional[str], message: str = 'Hello, World!') -> List[str]:
    return [message + (', ' + name if name else '')]  # Type hinting with default arguments
